Recorded the Million Dollar Weekend audiobook in Nov.

It took 24 full hours…

It was more difficult than I thought (and I’ve been doing YT and podcast for years)

It was totally worth it though.

Enjoy my soothing voice when it comes out on Jan 30. 😉

A few things I learned:

1/ Make sure to have professional producer with you - game changer - I had Scott Sherratt

2/ Speaking clearly is more important than speaking slowly or fast.

3/ Plan out if you want to do unscripted or share extra to audio listeners (“this is just for your audio listeners”) - I didn’t do this and wish I did

4/ Quality is key. It’s worth paying for studio (~$300 / day)- included sound engineer and $5k microphone among other things.

5/ Redo your intro on your last day - you know what you’re doing and the intro is the first part people listen to

6/ Compare comments from other audiobooks in your category, we researched all comments to pick out themes people liked and hated.

7/ Review your book BEFORE audiobook. You’re going to notice errors when reading and the more you can eradicate that BEFORE you start audio recording the better

8/ Bring a comfortable chair or make sure the one in studio is

9/ Bring chapstick, not sure why. Lips super chapped

10/ LOTS of caffeine, was surprised how draining 5+ hours of recording became

11/ I bought entrepreneur’s secret but any throat spray will do

If you want to build a business, stop confusing motion for action.

You don't need to take another $500 course or watch fake gurus on YouTube.

You need to start.

The BEST Part of Being Rich

When starting something new, follow The Law of 100. 

Put out 100 videos.
Record 100 podcasts.
Reach out to 100 potential customers. 

Get your reps in and you will see results.

Many people struggle to make their first dollar because they are so focused on how to make their first million.

Sure, plan ahead. But don’t get so caught up in the future that you forget to act in the present.

Most people: Overthink first, act later.
Successful entrepreneurs: Act first, figure it out later.

My beef with most business books:

They’re either too theoretical or too ‘recipe’.

But the truth is you need both.

Philosophy to explain WHY to do something. Practical to explain HOW.
NOW, not How.
